[2/30] P6 English Prelim ACSJ 2024 — Q10  Primary 6  (14.4s)
============================================================
STEM: “Had Jenny cut the apples earlier, we ___ lost so much time in preparing the dessert,” Peter lamented.
  (1) cannot have
  (2) will not have
  (3) could not have
  (4) would not have
ANSWER: (4)

ELABORATION (781 chars):
This question tests your knowledge of **Type 3 conditional sentences**, which describe an unreal situation in the past.

The sentence begins with the **past perfect tense** "Had Jenny cut" (meaning "If Jenny had cut"). For this rule, the second part of the sentence must use **would not have** plus the **past participle** ("lost") to show the imaginary result. This makes **(4)** the correct choice!

Here is why the other options are wrong:
**(1)** fails because "cannot have" uses the **present tense**, which mismatches the past condition.
**(2)** fails because "will not have" is a **future tense**, which does not fit an event that already happened.
**(3)** fails because "could not have" refers to an ability rather than a definite result, making the meaning illogical here.

