  (1) studied
  (2) was studying
  (3) was been studying
  (4) had been studying
ANSWER: 4

ELABORATION (668 chars):
This question tests the **past perfect continuous tense**, which shows an ongoing action in the past that continued up until another past event happened.

Because Sally's studying was an ongoing action ("for an hour") that happened before her teacher "arrived", we must use **had been studying**, making **(4)** correct.

**(1)** fails because "studied" is the **simple past tense** and doesn't show the duration leading up to the second event.
**(2)** fails because "was studying" is the **past continuous tense**, missing the connection to the later past event.
**(3)** fails because "was been studying" is grammatically incorrect; we never combine "was" and "been".

